text: Ok I just Piss, Crapped and Jizzed in my Pants all at once and it was very enlightening, forget everything else I want to see this yesterday, this actually happened, they have shown it on screen many times, in the movie Dragon, Wong Jack Man or the character that was portrayed on screen as him was the very best known Kung Fu specialist at the time and was recruited by the Kung Fu Masters who were upset that Bruce Lee was training Whites, Blacks or any nationality Wing Chun,¬†in the movie Dragon Wong Jack Man comes off as a hired Assassin of sorts and¬†he apparently challenged Bruce Lee to a fight in a Secret location, this fight happened behind closed doors and supposedly when Bruce was still heavy into using traditional form, in the movie it was a close fight and Wong Jack Man¬†did the equivalent of¬†a sucker punch to Bruce and Fractured his back, all this was heavily dramatized because no one really knows other than the fact that Bruce hurt his Back and was hospitalized for some time, in a rematch Bruce easily beat¬†Wong Jack Man again dramatized so who really knows, interesting to see how they portray this, I liked what I saw and whether it's truth or bullshit it is based on a true event so I cant wait, I'm not going to pick this apart like some people do and completely take the enjoyment out of the movie experience even before they see it, as for me I'm in 100%, BTW it shouldn't be but a couple more years before we start seeing new Bruce Lee movies, they tried to do this with Bruce Lee over 10 years ago when a company bought a license to use Bruce Lee's image and animate it using Super Computers to blend it into live action movies, the technology was still in it's infancy so it was ultimately postponed much like Avatar was postponed for many years till the tech caught up, this is coming sooner than you think

text: Again this is awful how they distort from reality. In the movie Dragon' The Bruce Lee Story (1993) Won Jack Man becomes responsible for Bruce Lee's back injury, for in reality Bruce Lee did a bad barbell move when training his back. In this they make won a hero and Bruce a almost villain. Bruce was well know for his short temper, but in his life he was for every one a role model after his crazy years as a teenager, he had become a very respectful person. He was real competitive and mostly demanding on himself, but he was respectful for his teachers, something Dan Inosanto still tell his audience in seminars. So what is this movie. I believe that the fight between Bruce and Won might have been more then the Lee clan tends to tell I believe Won most probably gave a better fight, but that Bruce did win.  None were  seriously injured from the fight and Bruce won the respect of the Chinese community has a real Kung Fu teacher. This BIRTH OF THE DRAGON movie is mostly fiction and his a disgrace to the memory of the man and genius in his own way that Bruce Lee was.  Read the Tao Of Jeet Kune Do, do a few martial arts styles for a few years then practice some of the Jun Fan Gung Fu (The form of Jeet Kune Do that was taught in Bruce Lee's kwan). Then you will understand how much Bruce understood the human body when it came to the possibility of using it martial arts. Otherwise it is just gossip when it comes to judge Bruce Lee. I practiced mostly Karate and Taii Jutsu with some Japanese weapon. I would never give up on my Tai jutsu techniques, but my way is no way so I incorporate like JKD philosophy suggest. I did some Jun Fan Gun Fu, but for me reading the Tao of Jeet Kune Do was more instructive, yet practicing JKD was good for learning real sparring skills with some contact fighting. I would like to learn more of Jung Fan Gung Fu, but the schools are a little expansive in my region. Jumg Fan Gung Fu is a style, where JKD is a philosophy. You can say I have my own JKD with very little Jun Fan Gung Fu in it

text: I hate to point out some very huge errors about this movie.   1) In the 60-70, china was in a political deadlock with america.  Basically, no chinese was allowed to go the usa unless they smuggled themselves across to hong kong and get on a plane to the states.  2)  Kung Fu or martial arts was not big during the 60s-70s because mao was telling every one to erase the old culture and embrace.  Basically the practice of kung fu was suppressed by communism 3) shaolin temple was not big in mainland china till Jet Li's Shaolin Temple in 1982.  Before 1982, years of communism have basically cleansed any followers of shaolin in mainland.  while, hong kong has maintained shaolin temple as some kind of rebel base for martial art practitioners, shaolin temple was practically dead.  Jet Li did an interview years ago about his experience of making the movie.  During the interview, he described the temple was practically emptied and no one was working there.   in conclusion, the idea of some shaolin monk can travel to the states freely and can knows kung fu is full of bull shit.  In reality, a lot of the bruce lee stories are just legends.

author: Merlijn Bell

text: This movie seems entertaining but seems more fiction/myth portrayal than fact based/eye witnessed based. The whole fight was based on whether or not Bruce Lee could teach non-Chinese kung fu. This movie seems to portray Lee overly arrogant and in a negative light and Won Jack as a more pure individual. Bruce Lee did have an ego for a period but ultimately overcame his ego in later years. I just don't like the negative portrayal it seems to give to Bruce Lee. He wasn't fighting Won Jack to prove his new kung fu is better than the old (traditional) kung fu or to please his ego. He was fighting so that he can teach whoever he wanted and not simply just Chinese (which was what the San Francisco Chinese community wanted, to keep kung fu only among Chinese).

text: I don't get, why so many people are complaining, this looks like an accurate portrayal of Bruce Lee to me. He WAS a giant douche and an arrogant prick and the actor is doing great portraying him as such. He thought he was the greatest fighter in the world. Yes he was a world class fighter, but THE greatest? Not really and saying you are the greatest, repeatedly, makes you look douchey. Also, while we might never find out the truth about the fight between Bruce Lee and Wong Jack Man, both sides claimed, they won and in fact, if you do some research it is actually more likely, that Bruce lost and then lied about it. Now before you write an angry response and try to insult me, just read up on the different reports from people who witnessed the fight and you will see, there are different stories out there and after reading them I have to agree with the side, that says Bruce lost.

text: Finally a movie that shows Bruce Lee as he really was. People forget he was in his 20's when he did most of what he was famous for, he was still a kid and he didn't have time to grow and mature.  Lee was described by many people that knew him as a cocky egomaniac, plus his fight was Wong Jack Man was brought about because he had no respect for anyone else in the martial arts community, including his elders.¬† The account of that fight from Wong Jack Man is far more believable than the multiple versions given by Lee‚Äôs side.¬† Wong said the fight lasted 20 minutes, ended with no winner, was stopped because Lee was too winded to continue (which Lee himself backed up), and during the match Lee actually tried to kill him while Wong held back.¬† No one knows whose version is true but there is anecdotal evidence to support Wong‚Äôs version while the version from Lee is self-serving since he was trying to build his legend and Linda is trying to profit from it.

text: I loved Bruce Lee from the moment I saw him in Enter the Dragon. But it was only later in my life, when I learned a bit more about his own personal life, that I finally understood him as a person, not just as an icon. And I think the commenter that said this movie might wind up downplaying him is right. Based on this trailer, I think the movie intends to portray him as nothing more than some martial artist too skilled for his own good who's trying to prove something. I sincerely hope I'm wrong, because truth be told, the trailer really hyped me up. I've been waiting for so long for an even remotely biographical movie about Bruce Lee... But oh... wait.. . herein lies the articulate douchiness of these moviemakers... The movie doesn't seem to be about Bruce Lee at all, just some white guy that met him -- movie based on the life of a true legend, but centered around just another white lead.   Well, I choose to stay optimistic, if only to hold on to the hope that this movie won't completely suck proverbial ass.

text: Well, despite all of the negative comments, I think this movie should be good. We already are familiar with Bruce Lee's upbringing, studying Kung Fu and acting while he was growing up in China; and him becoming a Martial Artist and instructor in America, primarily for sport and entertainment (also street); versus a humble Shaolin Monk, also from China, who actually allowed Martial Arts as his primary way of life, more than just for money and for fame. It's all about a time where Bruce Lee had to humble himself and he had to remember to always be true to his roots.

text: Why so much hate for this? You guys haven't even seen the film yet. They have to show controversial material to get people to buy tickets. If the trailer had Bruce Lee simply walking the streets turning the other cheek to every bum who wanted to pick a fight just to make himself some good ol' green tea at the end of the day NO ONE WOULD BUY TICKETS. Look, they wouldn't have been able to make this picture without Shannon Lee's approval, she owns the rights to her father's name, likeness, property etc etc. Take my word for it, you will see multiple sides of Bruce in this movie. I for one am more than excited to see this film and personally? I don't think there could be a better way to make a new Bruce Lee installment. I think you guys are all afraid of the fact that this movie humanizes Bruce. You're all so fixated on him being this mythological figure who transcends time and space. Don't get me wrong, he was and will always be a legend but there was a time when he was just a man unsure of his future. Things happened to work out well for him because he was abnormally committed and talented. I was one of those dorky kids that chose to make every high school paper somehow related to Bruce Lee because yea I was THAT much of a fan but my memory regarding his history is a little blurred. If this film is in any way factual and truthful to real life events... It's going to be fucking incredible.   Be water bitches.

text: From interviews and other sources Bruce Lee was actually quite humble by the time he became a teacher. Confident as hell but still humble. He actually studied with a lot of martial arts teachers who today would be considered his lesser. He didn't care, he wanted to learn and perfect his craft. He accepted the challenge to fight the monk out of respect and to not bow down to pressure from the Chinese community to not teach Kung-Fu to non Chinese. In the latter part of his short life he fully embraced Buddhist philosophy not just in Kung-Fu but in life in general. Watch some of his TV interviews you'll see confidence, not cocky arrogance. This movie kinda reminds me of Iron and Silk where a white guy is used as a centre point for a Kung-Fu movie that features superior Chinese characters.

text: I am curious. Has anyone here actually had experience with the Jeet Kun Do family? I did. My sifu was Lamar Davis, who was trained by Larry Hartsell. Bruce was mildly arrogant. In fact, Hollywood execs once begged Gene LeBell to come and try to calm him down. It ended with Mr. LeBell holding Bruce for some 20 minutes in a judo hold. Bruce later asked him to show him how to do what he did. I will see this, just because I respect Lee Jun Fan's legacy. Sigong Lee went against the traditionalists and many were not happy. Before you venture an opinion, do some research, or visit a Jeet Kun Do studio. They're not as common today as 25 years ago, but you'll find that Bruce was on the one hand easy to work with and on the other, a very difficult man to work with.

text: Okay, everyone is flipping out over this lol.  Watch the movie first, then freak out.  I, personally haven't seen it yet, but I want to.  Being Asian, I'm not offended.  ONE, Bruce taught white people and thus angered the Asian world.  The white guy is very much a part of the movie.  He is the ONLY white student we see (might be due to budget lol otherwise there might have been more), so he was probably to emphasize the dramatics of Bruce accepting the first white student. Bruce spent most his life in America.  I don't doubt that "kick ass" attitude brushed off on him. When Bruce studied under Yip Man, he had quite the playful attitude and spunk as a kid.  In his journal, he struggled to grasp the peaceful mind of gung fu.  All he could see was wanting to beat the other person (thus, kick ass).  Who knows if he fully grasp the gung ku peace of mind or if he did but then changed when he came to America?   So overall, the whole story was probably twisted by the media.  So why are we freaking out about a white man telling Bruce's story when that's probably what happened when he lived in where was it? San Francisco?? Can't we all just enjoy a movie if its good because NO story was ever told the way it happened. Didn't history teach you that? XD

text: Well, I think I just found a "Bruce Lee" movie to boycott for being a complete misrepresentation of him.   Anyone that has ever truly studied Bruce Lee's history knows he was not the way they are trying to depict him here. He was a very philosophical man who NEVER taught people to "kick ass". He was always about kung fu being a combination of the mind, heart, and body. He was always seeking enlightenment through meditation his art. His goal with his style was create a formless style of martial art so as to overcome what he saw as a weakness of limitations by locking yourself into a single form.  I will not be watching this rubbish no matter how good the action is claimed to be.

text: No doubt the movie will be entertaining, but don't regard this as a history of Bruce Lee or an accurate depiction. We all know that Bruce was much faster than the actor playing him and that he had to be told to slow down in real life when the movie makers were trying to film him. Bruce had learned his trade formally, but the greater edge he had came from his experience as a street fighter. He had already decided not to tie himself to any one form and used each and every style as necessary during a fight. He certainly would not have needed any form of lecturing about his fighting style from anyone albeit he would be respectful.

text: this is such a farce...will anyone ever do this historically right? this fight actually took place in a kwoon with very few people as witness. Bruce did prevail but the actual combat was not anything like it is being depicited in this chop socky nonsense. Bruce actually struggled somewhat according to his wife Linda who was there to see it. It is on record. She herself has stated that Bruce was disappointed with how he fought. He became winded and that is when he began cross training to increase his stamina and endurance. I have studied under the direction one of the very few of Bruce Lee's actual original students from the 60s and have been a 30 years student of his life and philosophies...this movie is garbage just as Dragon was sensationalized hollywood bullshit. Disappointing to say the least.

Wong's people said it lasted 20 minutes, from what's been stated Bruce had the advantage in the fight but both men eventually called it quits when they became exhausted. text: This movie is not only an absolute disgrace to the legacy of Bruce Lee and his family, it's extremely disrespectful to Asians who consider Bruce Lee a major Civil Rights figure who fought for fair treatment and social equality. I find it interesting that in his own lifetime, Bruce Lee faced discrimination in Hollywood and had to go to Hong Kong to achieve any real success. Yet even now in death, Hollywood writers Christopher Wilkinson and Stephen Rivele, along with director, George Nolfi, give him similar treatment by dishonoring and rewriting his history, his philosophy, and his life. Bruce Lee was a philosophical man who faced racism as an Asian American and who overcame it with the strength of his abilities and personality. He wasn't some arrogant jerk who went around trying to "kick ass." Maybe for their next Biopic, Mr. Wilkinson and Rivele can tell the story of Martin Luther King Jr. and how he was a power-hungry egomaniac. Make sure the main protagonist is a white guy who gets the Black girl in the end too!

text: Watched dozens of Bruce Lee movies growing up in the 80's and 90's, read a fair share of stories and a few biographies on him, too. I'm mixed-race Asian myself, so go figure I idolized the guy.  I am finding it INFINITELY hilarious that so many people are calling white washing or saying this does not represent Bruce Lee accurately. The hell it doesn't! Read up on him,  you ignorant bastards. He was arrogant as hell at the time, and he had not developed Jeet Kun Do yet or the several words of wisdom to go along with it.  1:30 to 2:15 is probably the closest the world will ever get of Bruce Lee's youth replicated by human acting. It is spot fucking on, and I am sure they used old footage to direct the post-match strut at 2:02. This movie looks like it will do the man's history justice. He wasn't born a sage, he grew into one.
author: Indefinite

text: As a Hong Kong American, I agree there is an unfortunate element of whitewashing, as Hollywood never feels secure enough that a Chinese actor (or any asian actor) could carry a film to a successful box office as the lead role (heck not even TWO proven successful stars, such as Jackie Chan AND Jet Li together! Hence the white kid in Forbidden Kingdom). In an ideal world, Bruce would be the main character, not some caucasian no name disciple we couldn't care less about. The idea that white audiences are unable to relate to an asian main character and needs to view the asian experience through a white filter is frankly unacceptable in this day and age. Imagine if instead of Bruce Lee and his life defining fight, this biopic was about the circumstances around Ali and his fight with Foreman. Do you think having a white protagonist as the curating viewpoint would be ideal in that hypothetical film? If not, then this film's approach isn't either.   However, I do appreciate the casting choices for Bruce Li and Wong Jackman. Philip Ng is a rising martial arts star in the current (strinking) Hong Kong film industry. He is also a Hong Kong American, so coupled with his physical ability, he has the right circumstances to portray Bruce Lee. Yu Xia is a longtime legit serious actor from mainland China, like the equivalent of a Ben Kingsley or Liam Neeson before they sold out to shitty movies. Though he's not a martial artist like Ng, his reputation as a great actor makes him a prime choice to play a contrasting stoic, level headed monk. So at least they didn't botch the casting.  EDIT: Remember, guys, this is pre-JKD, pre philosophy self help book Bruce Lee. And also a commericial action film. So accuracy be damned, it's got to be exciting!

Finally were talking a grandmaster..the degree of training and skill to reach that level...Bruce Lee did not beat a grandmaster in 3 min no contest. Maybe instead of being fanboys you actually study the fight from both angles and then consider the word of a punk and an egomanic vs a monk and respected martial artist master. Not saying Bruce did not become great but at first he was just a punk with a chip on his shoulder

text: Not another Bruce Lee movie. I studied directly under Grandmaster Wong, Ark-Yuey and taught all of his private lessons for more than 10 years. He knew Bruce Lee and his family. He said that when he met Bruce Lee he was nothing but a skinny, smart-mouth kid. Then, when Lee went to Hong Kong he came back a year or so later and he had all these muscles. Sifu said that muscles like that can't be made in a year. He was cocky. I saw a filmed interview with him and he was rather angry with every response during it. As the story goes, there was a TV program in Hong Kong. Several masters were invited as well as Bruce Lee. One of the masters was demonstrating how strong his horse was; no one could push him off of it or take him down. Bruce Lee came up and kicked the master in his face, turned around and said, "I don't push, I kick." That didn't sit him well with the other masters in Hong Kong. He was good at what he did. One of the people who knew him in Hong Kong and studied with Yip Man was Hawkins Chang. He has a whole different story to tell about Bruce Lee than what you've been hearing. In an interview with Charlie Rose all Jackie Chan said about Bruce Lee was that he helped his stunt group started in movies and made kung fu look like real fighting. That's it. I know I'll get a lot of nasty comments from Bruce Lee lovers.  They simply want to believe something other than what is presented to them. As one of the commentators stated, Shannon Lee does not approve of this movie.

text: From what I understand Bruce Lee took great pride in showing the realism of kung fu in his movies. He spent his life trying to show western cultures that there was more to eastern cultures than the stereotypical bull that hollywood was putting out. He was spiritual, philosophical and kind. He allowed anyone, no matter their race or creed to be taught kung fu in a time when it was unheard of in the Chinese community. Then he stopped teaching almost completely  (except for a lucky few) because he saw that people took his word as gospel when he was seeking innovation within his art. And if I also remember correctly it was this fight with a tradition Chinese monk that would determine whether or not he would be able to teach those who were outside of the community. And then he had to catch up to him because the monk ran away for three minutes until Bruce was able to catch him and beat him fairly easily. This movie takes so much away from the inspiring life of a man who was truly one of kind. This is a disgrace to everything that he had been trying to do for his culture, his art, and it is a disgrace to his legacy. (This is only valid if this trailer is truly representative to what the movie will ultimately be, which, knowing how the movie industry misrepresents things all the time, we know could be true.)

text: Everyone keeps going on about Lee being a 'secondary' character in the film. Did they actually watch the trailer? It's about Lee's famous Chinatown SF fight with Wong Jack Man. It's not about Lee only, per se, but about a clash of two different views on martial arts, and how Lee's vision of fighting won the day. How Lee's arrogance became the norm for martial arts in the West. Lee's mother was a half-Chinese, half-Caucasian Christian, and he developed a somewhat Western attitude towards martial arts, arguably¬†via his exposure to Hollywood. At least that's my take on it. Like everyone else offering opinions here on what the movie is about, and how big a role lee's character actually plays, I haven't seen the film¬†yet. For the record, I'm Asian, and not at all offended at the presence of the Steve McQueen character in the story.

text: Yep, another reconstruction history that favorites China.  The reason Bruce had to fight Wong is because the Chinese martial arts teachers in San Fran doesn't approve Bruce is teaching "foreigners" Kung-Fu (back then it's a taboo).  So they force Bruce to fight Wong (their best fighter, who was trained in the arts of Shaolin) and made Bruce promised if Bruce loses, he would stop teaching foreigners.  Bruce of course said yes, but Wong insisted on a closed-door fight instead of open contest, Bruce again agreed to it.  What really happened remains a mystery as both sides claimed victorious, but the end result is Bruce continues to teach foreigners so it's pretty obvious he won.  However, after the fight against Wong it made Bruce rethink about his techniques and he created the slogan: "techniques and forms are prisons of true Kung-Fu fighting" and seek to mix East and West martial arts and create a new form of "free flow Kung Fu" which he later called "Jeer Quan Dao" (the preview made it seem like it was the monk that taught Bruce to go beyond technique, that is a blatant no as Chinese martial arts are rigid techniques and forms).

text: I¬† trained with Bruce's best fighter/student ¬†from the China Town era for 17 years, who also was invited and went to Bruce's house on Sunday's to train, and was friend's with Bruce and his wife Linda. Bob Bremer, aka the China Town Ass Kicker, told many colorful, amazing, and interesting stories about himself nd Bruce Lee. One of them was the infamous fight with Wong Jack Man. The real story is that Bruce began an evolution of his style after the Wong Jack Man fight and ended up creating JKD because of the limitations he had imposed on himself from his modified Wing Chun at that era of his evolution. The way Bob tells it, is that Bruce was amazed with Wong Jack..., amazed because he never met anyone in his life that could run backwards as fast as Wong was running, while Bruce was trying to chase him down with his straight blast!!! He told Bob, That Wong was flailing his arms in a backwards swimming motion, while running backwards and Bruce had a hard time catching him, and got out of breath. He eventually did catch him and beat him till he gave up. But it was this limitation of being able to get to Wong faster that got Bruce even more motivated to create the perfect style, and perfect himself into the perfect fighting machine. This movie B.S, just like the Dragon story, that this was some competition between equals is bull crap, Wong never laid a hand on him. Total B.S!

Lol Due to that movie, he discovered the real Bruce Lee, became involved in JEET KUNE DO, Bruce Lee's personal martial art. He's studied JKD now now for 20 years, he has met his Lee's Widow, Linda Lee and Dan Inosanto Lee's best friend and Martial Artist, on numerous occasions, having traveled from the UK to America numerous times to meet other people with the same shared passion and love for Bruce Lee  And it all started with a fabricated movie...

text: Movie sticks white guy in sea of Asian leads and extras. Hollywood is racist because they cast too many whites.  This makes about as much sense as the 2015 Oscar nonsense. Blacks make up 12% of the U.S. population. Blacks are cast in ~12% of leading roles. Hollywood still racist. If a white guy made a movie like any of Tyler Perry's films, he'd get death threats. The double-standard is ridiculous.  If you want racism to disappear, stop whining about something you perceive to be racism. If the world does take a sharp turn for the worst (which it is not, you've just been conditioned to think so), it's because non-issues (like fake racism) have been detracting from actual problems (like real racism) since the dawn of social media.  If you fancy yourself an intelligent and discerning individual, give what you read and hear some critical thought every now and then.

text: When they have Bruce Lee being aided by "Matrix" style wire work, nothing is okay anymore. You can go ahead and "wire-work" anyone else you want- Keanu Reeves, Lawrence Fishburne, even Tony Jaa.  But don't dare insult Bruce Lee with that.  This is what sacrilege looks like.  This is what soulless cash-grabbing looks like.  Are you fucking kidding me? Bruce Lee, jumping down from about 10 feet high, and then practically floating down like he was plugged in?  Fuck you.   This is like making a documentary about Jesus, and describing Satan tempting him on the Mount as a "Matrix-style" fistfight.  That's not hyperbole.  Bruce Lee is to martial arts what Jesus is to Christianity.  IN other words, you can't have one without the other. There's a reason for that, which deserves a movie worthy of Lee.  (Jesus already has his movie masterpieces)  Bruce Lee will probably never get a good movie about him made.  But wire-work?  That's just morally wrong.

text: As a practitioner of martial arts, a fan a Sifu Lee, and a realist, this movie's trailer tried to sell people on it being about Bruce Lee when in fact it isn't. Every "based or inspired by a true story or events" movie has it's "magic" injected into it, but this one here...where do I start? First, my Sifu, whom I won't mention his name, defended this movie because HIS Sifu is Philip Ng, so of course he's going to defend him, but I disagreed with him, especially because I felt his energy and I knew the man knew I was right, as well as the many fans of Sifu Lee knows this also. Next, is it that difficult for Hollywood to stop white washing every movie that is supposed to have colored people in it, especially when it's about true living or dead people?? Take the story of Jesus for example and pretty much EVERY Bible character in every Biblical movie I have watched on Netflix and they are ALL white actors. Seriously Hollywood?? Fine, we've never actually seen Jesus, so paint him however you think he looks like, but a man like Bruce Lee, where EVERYONE knows what he looks like and 90% of people know what he did, you can't just promote a movie to make it look like it's about him and have him sidelined. He fought Hollywood on that when he was alive and this movie does the same thing again. I give it zero stars for misleading and the horrible "Crouching Tiger Hidden Dragon" style of floating in the air. Something Bruce Lee stayed away from when directing his own films. Ok, I'm done.

text: Bruce Lee was not an asshole. He was also not arrogant, and he was very respectful of the tradition of Martial Arts. If Hollywood is trying to piss off every Bruce Lee fan by releasing this horrible misrepresentation of Bruce Lee, they will without a doubt succeed. For anyone who doesn't know Bruce or what he was like when he was alive, he was pretty much a real life Goku. He was very nice and polite, and innocent, and only wanted to be the best fighter in the world for the sake of discovering how good he can become and to test the limations of humans, and he did achieve this title, without a doubt (which is a title he still holds to this day, since not a single man, woman, or even machine can recreate the amazing things he achieved in his life). He was also very wise for his age, and if you watch any interview with him you will realise just how special he really was. This piece of shit movie will ruin his legend for ever. Shame on Hollywood. I will boycott this movie for the sake of Bruce Lee and the legendary legacy he left behind. There will never, ever, be another man like Bruce. Hollywood should show it's god damn respects instead of turning him into an asshole in a movie about his legend 20 years after his death. What a joke.

text: Bodhidharma was a Buddhist monk who lived in ancient India during the 5th or 6th century when the famous and mighty Hindu Gupta empire was in full serge in India. He is traditionally credited as the transmitter of Chan Buddhism to China, and regarded as its first Chinese patriarch. Although Bodhidharma embraced Buddhism earlier he hailed from the Kshatriya Hindu caste and as per ancient Indian tradition kshatriya caste was regarded as the warrior caste of India. Being a kshatriya Bodhidharma learned the skill of ancient Indian sword fighting, archery and melee attack skills. Within a few years Bodhidharma achieved mastery in all forms of ancient Indian martial arts and later after embracing Buddhism when he travelled back to China he combined all the deadly techniques of ancient Indian martial arts and create another new form of martial arts which combines some deadly combos of ancient Indian fencing, archery and melee attaking skiills. Later this form of martial arts became very popular among Shaolin group of Buddhism and came to be known as "Kung-Fu". text: "Technique is a trap; style is a prison. Kung Fu is meant to liberate." "Kung Fu is self discipline and self discovery."  Beautifully scripted. Masterfully choreographed. Whether Mr Lee was like that (arrogant and short sighted initially) or not, the story is fascinating and the lesson for any future practitioner, is powerful. The lesson - you are limited if you cannot adapt. You are constrained if you cannot improvise. The truth - Every great person has to start somewhere; they may excel rapidly like Lee, but most of us with less self awareness will take a longer road to discovery. Lee would have had a remarkable degree of self-discipline.
